I&#x27;ve spent a lot of time in both domains, and the Python-style half-open interval is the clear winner, because it produces the fewest &quot;+1&quot; and &quot;-1&quot;, <i>each and every one</i> of which is <i>begging</i> to be a bug. I disagree with Dijkstra on some other counts, but in this case he is correct, both in theory and in practice.<p>It&#x27;s easier today than it used to be 1 indexed, though, because there are more languages that support some form of<p><pre><code>    for element in collection: ...
</code></pre>
instead of the <i>incredibly</i> error-prone<p><pre><code>    for (int i = 0; i < something; i++) { ... }
</code></pre>
Or, was it<p><pre><code>    for (int i = 0; i <= something; i++) { ... }
</code></pre>
Or was it<p><pre><code>    for (int i = 1; i <= something + 1; i++) { ...}
</code></pre>
You have fewer places to make fencepost errors when you use the first style, so the costs of 1-based indexing are fewer. They&#x27;re still higher than Python-style, though, because in Python you have both the correct for loop and still have the correct intervals.
